import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Column-by-column exploration

# Specifies the list of columns, excluding the target variable
columns_to_explore = [col for col in df.columns if col != 'y']

# This will loop through each column and apply appropriate exploration techniques
for column in columns_to_explore:
    print(f"Exploration of '{column}':")
    print("-" * 40)

    # Gets the data type of the column
    dtype = df[column].dtype
    print(f"Data Type: {dtype}")

    # Perform this if the column is categorical
    if dtype == 'object':
        # This will print unique values and counts
        print(f"Unique Values in '{column}':\n{df[column].value_counts()}\n")

        # Plots a bar plot for categorical features
        plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
        sns.countplot(data=df, x=column, palette="viridis")
        plt.title(f"Count Plot for '{column}'")
        plt.xlabel(column)
        plt.ylabel("Count")
        plt.xticks(rotation=45)
        plt.show()

    # If the column is numerical (continuous or discrete)
    else:
        # then their descriptive statistics will be calculated
        mean = df[column].mean()
        median = df[column].median()
        std_dev = df[column].std()
        min_val = df[column].min()
        max_val = df[column].max()

        print(f"Mean: {mean}")
        print(f"Median: {median}")
        print(f"Standard Deviation: {std_dev}")
        print(f"Minimum: {min_val}")
        print(f"Maximum: {max_val}")

        # Plots histogram and boxplot for numerical features
        fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))

        # Histogram
        sns.histplot(df[column], kde=True, ax=axes[0], color='skyblue')
        axes[0].set_title(f"Histogram of '{column}'")
        axes[0].set_xlabel(column)
        axes[0].set_ylabel("Frequency")

        # Boxplot
        sns.boxplot(data=df, x=column, ax=axes[1], color='lightcoral')
        axes[1].set_title(f"Boxplot of '{column}'")
        axes[1].set_xlabel(column)

        plt.tight_layout()
        plt.show()

    print("\n" + "-"*50 + "\n")

Column by Column Explanation for One-Hot Coding:

It is important to utilize one-hot encoding in order to convert categorical columns with multiple categories into separate binary columns (0 or 1) for each category. This allows machine learning algorithms to interpret categorical data as numerical values, which is necessary for data processing.

Column-by-Column Explanation for One-Hot Encoding

The following are columns in the dataframe that contain categorical data that need to be converted in to numerical data (binary) through one-hot encoding.

•	workclass: This is a categorical variable representing the type of employer or work sector. One-hot encoding will create binary columns for each unique workclass such as workclass_Private, workclass_Self-emp-not-inc, etc.
•	education: contains values “High School”, “Bachelor”, “Master”. It will become three columns: education_High School, education_Bachelor, and education_Master.
•	marital-status: This categorical variable will be one-hot encoded (e.g., marital-status_Married, marital-status_Single, etc.).
•    occupation: This is a categorical variable indicating the type of job held. One-hot encoding will create columns for each unique occupation (e.g., occupation_Exec_Managerial, occupation_Craft-repair, etc.).
•    relationship: This categorical variable will be one-hot encoded to represent relationships (e.g., relationship_Husband, relationship_Wife, etc.).
•	race: This is a categorical variable that will be one-hot encoded to create columns for each race (e.g., race_White, race_Black, etc.).
•	sex: This categorical variable will be one-hot encoded to create columns for each sex (e.g., sex_Male, sex_Female).
•	native-country with multiple unique values: Each unique country becomes its own binary column.
•	y: The target variable is a categorical variable because it is either <=50K or >50K, which is not continuous and can use binary classification, so it needs to be encoded into a binary format.
In [26]:
# One-hot encode the predictor dataframe
df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df, drop_first=True)
In [27]:
# shows the shape of dataframe before and after encoding
print("Original DataFrame Shape:", df.shape)
print("Encoded DataFrame Shape:", df_encoded.shape)

Original DataFrame Shape: (32561, 14)
Encoded DataFrame Shape: (32561, 100)

Difference Pre and Post Encoding:

Pre: In the pre-encoding dataframe, categorical columns were represented with a single column per feature, even if they contained multiple categories (e.g., “gender” had only one column for both “Male” and “Female”).

Post: After encoding, now each unique category in the categorical columns became its own binary column (e.g., “gender_Male” and “gender_Female”). This transformation increased the number of columns in the dataset, making it wider. For instance, if we had 5 categorical columns with 3 unique categories each, we added approximately 10 new columns. After Encoding: Each unique category is represented by its own binary column, increasing the number of columns and allowing machine learning algorithms to interpret the categorical data numerically.

How has the shape changed?

Before encoding, the dataframe had fewer columns because each categorical column was represented by a single column, regardless of how many unique values (categories) it contained.

After encoding, the dataframe’s shape changed, the number of columns increased substanially. Each categorical variable now has multiple columns, one for each category. For example, a column with three categories would become three new binary columns.
